The paper discusses conflict-driven clause learning (CDCL) SAT-solvers, which are commonly used in artificial intelligence (AI) applications. The paper also introduces a model and language for discussing CDCL-based proof systems, which falls under the category of logic in computer science (cs.LO). Additionally, the paper involves the study of decision strategies and clause learning, which could be categorized under algorithms and data structures (cs.DS) or programming languages (cs.PL). Finally, the paper involves theoretical results and proofs, which could be categorized under computational complexity (cs.CC).
